Test 2, STAT 245 for sab78

Author

STAT 245 Fall 2023

Response variable

Fit a regression model using as your response variable: the number of genes a bacteria has (in a certain location, of a certain type).

Data Access

You can find your data at: https://sldr.netlify.app/data/social-plasmids.csv

Context

This dataset was recently analyzed by Anna Dewar and colleagues in the paper Genes for cooperation are not more likely to be carried by plasmids.

The authors say,

Cooperation is prevalent across bacteria, but risks being exploited by non-cooperative cheats.

One idea about how genes that make bacteria more likely to cooperate persist in the population is that those genes might be shared from one bacteria to another when they exchange plasmids (small packets of DNA that get transferred from one bacterium to another when the are in contact.) So Dewar and collegues note that:

A key prediction of this hypothesis is that genes which are more likely to be transferred, such as those on plasmids, should be more likely to code for cooperative traits. Testing this prediction requires identifying all genes for cooperation in bacterial genomes. However, previous studies used a method which likely misses some of these genes for cooperation. To solve this, we used a new genomics tool, SOCfinder, which uses three distinct modules to identify all kinds of genes for cooperation.

And they claim their data show that:

bacteria carry very few of their genes for cooperative traits on plasmid(s) (average = 6 genes), despite plasmids generally carrying a total number of genes that is much greater than the total genes for cooperation in the genome (average of 208 plasmid genes per genome versus an average of 93 genes for cooperative traits per genomeâ¦

Can you confirm any of their findings with your analysis?

Variables in the data set include:

  • Variables about the bacterium:
    • its genome_accession number (a unique ID), and its
    • phylum, class, order, family, genus, and species â the groupings in that list go from larger ones to smaller, that is, each phylum can include multiple classes, and each class multiple orders, etc.
    • the metabolism the bacterium uses to get its energy
  • location of the genes in question (either on a âchromosomeâ, the main pool of DNA, or on a âplasmidâ, the smaller bits of DNA that might be exchanged by interacting bacteria)
  • gene_type: whether the genes in question have a role in social behavior or not
  • n_genes: the total number of genes that this bacterium has in this location, of this gene_type.
